### Background

As a part of the  [Dllmap feature](https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/pull/19373) we need to expose  `LoadLibrary` and `GetEntrypoint` functions.

We also need to define two events specific respectively to loading a library and to determining an entrypoint. The runtime will execute two callbacks to managed code on each dll load attempt. The user’s code can subscribe to these callbacks and define any mapping strategy. 

### Proposed API

**NativeLibrary** 

Abstraction for NativeLibrary class, a helper class for loading native libraries and extracting entrypoints.
```c#
namespace System.Runtime.InteropServices
{
    public static partial class NativeLibrary
    {
        public static NativeLibrary Load(string libraryName);
        public static NativeLibrary Load(string libraryName, DllImportSearchPath dllImportSearchPath, Assembly assembly);
        public IntPtr Handle { get; }
        public string Name { get; }
        public IntPtr GetNativeEntrypoint(string symbolName);
    }
}
```
If the library or the entrypoint can't be found, `Load `and `GetNativeEntrypoint `return null.

**Load library / get entrypoint specific events**

The call-back registration will be per-assembly, whether using events or not. Each assembly needs to register for the callback. DllMap initialization logic can subscribe to AssemblyLoad event to register for the callback on every assembly load.

**_Using events_**

```c#
namespace System.Reflection
{
    public delegate IntPtr LoadNativeLibraryDelegate(string libraryName, DllImportSearchPath dllImportSearchPath, Assembly callingAssembly);
    public delegate IntPtr GetEntrypointDelegate(string libraryName, string entrypointName);

    public abstract partial class Assembly
    {
        // proposed members
        public event LoadNativeLibraryDelegate LoadNativeLibrary;
        public event GetEntrypointDelegate GetNativeEntrypoint;
    }
}
```

**_Alternative: Using callbacks_**

Generally, the runtime raises events only after trying default logic and failing. But in this case, we want the callbacks to run as the first priority. So, registering callbacks is considered to be more suited for the CoreCLR's style. It does not have the overhead of raising the event/handling - it's just a qcall.
```c#
namespace System.Reflection
{
    public delegate IntPtr LoadNativeLibraryDelegate(string libraryName, DllImportSearchPath dllImportSearchPath, Assembly callingAssembly);
    public delegate IntPtr GetEntrypointDelegate(string libraryName, string entrypointName);

    public abstract partial class Assembly
    {
        // proposed members
        public LoadNativeLibraryDelegate RegisterNativeLibraryLoadCallBack(LoadNativeLibraryDelegate callBack);
        public GetEntrypointDelegate RegisterGetEntrypointCallBack(GetEntrypointDelegate callBack);
    }
}

```

We have considered placing the delegates (or callbacks) in the AssemblyLoadContext. Finally, we think that the Assemby is a better place because it enables to define a more customized (per-assembly) behavior and gets user more control over what's going on.

### Open questions

- What mechanism should be used for per assembly callback registration: events or callbacks?

* This class has gotten very big and contains several groups of unrelated functionality;
* Usefulness of deriving from NodeFactory is questionable, it seems we're using just a fraction of its functionality and overlaps in the various helper names cause repeated aliasing issues;
* If it turns out to be possible to cleanly separate ReadyToRunCodegenNodeFactory from NodeFactory, we should either split it into several classes or at least make it a partial class living in several files:
    * CorInfoImpl utility functions for constructing the various helper cells and signatures;
    * Token collection and lookup engine;
* R2R header table collection management.

* Command-line specifies a number of "input files" that get all compiled into a single output R2R PE executable;
* Today architecture will need minor tweaks as we won't have a pre-existing MSIL to start off;
* All input files will be part of the CompilationModuleGroup without any singled-out assembly;
* This is expected to require additional CoreCLR runtime changes to work properly end-to-end;
* This will require a 2-level MethodEntrypointTable to cater for method tables for the individual modules and perhaps a new R2R component module table;
* Alternatively we might want to keep the pre-existing functionality untouched and just add a completely new entrypoint table format specific to the multi-module build.
